The Martha Complex

Rachel: Gwyneth is a celebrity and a founder, which are two different thing=
s, but she=E2=80=99s combined them in a way that magnifies each of those ro=
les. Goop remains an anomaly when it comes to celebrity-founded brands beca=
use, typically, celebrities are founders in name only. Famous people usuall=
y lend their likeness, and involvement in their brands is more similar to a=
 licensing agreement. Gwyneth=E2=80=99s obviously way more than that=E2=80=
=93=E2=80=93she truly built a business influenced by her absurd life. Every=
one wants to do that, but no one else has in this way. She=E2=80=99s this A=
cademy Award-winning actress, a media staple for decades, a style icon, etc=
etera=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and then she actually started a real business that=
=E2=80=99s authentic to her, like a modern Martha Stewart. She=E2=80=99s an=
 outlier, and that=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99re talking about her now, 16 ye=
ars in.

Lauren: What place does Goop serve in the ecosystem of the startup world?

Rachel: If we look at contemporary brands in beauty or fashion that were fo=
unded between 2008 and 2012, they either became profitable or they disappea=
red. Goop is not profitable, but it=E2=80=99s still around and still extrem=
ely relevant, with outsize influence compared to the actual size of the bus=
iness. A friend texted me the other day after reading Line Sheet and said, =
=E2=80=9CI had no idea, I thought Goop was doing really well,=E2=80=9D beca=
use Gwyneth is portrayed and covered in the media as this really successful=
 C.E.O. with a strong business. That was her perception, at least. If not f=
or Gwyneth=E2=80=99s relevance in culture, I don=E2=80=99t know if Goop wou=
ld be around.

Lauren: When Goop started, it had so much traction because Paltrow is a gre=
at editor. She has a point of view, and she=E2=80=99s not afraid to present=
 it. The content was exciting, fun, juicy, and
entertaining. Then they started layering in other advertising and commercia=
l opportunities, which makes sense. There=E2=80=99s a multibrand retail exp=
erience, a fast-casual food vertical, her clothing, beauty, and more. Indiv=
idually, these are all interesting businesses, but altogether, that sort of=
 diversification can create a cloudy revenue picture and make a company a l=
ot less attractive to sell. When you look at the trajectory=E2=80=94launchi=
ng in 2008, getting advertising pretty quickly thereafter, opening multibra=
nd retail in the early 2010s, then launching products afterward, and now le=
aning into food=E2=80=94when do you think the business became more complica=
ted to sell?

Rachel: What was originally captivating, and what remains captivating, is G=
wyneth=E2=80=99s point of view. People wanted to read that initial newslett=
er because she has good taste. We wanted to know what she was eating, what =
exercise she was doing, where she was going, tips for the best hotels, all =
of
those things. That=E2=80=99s what people wanted to know from her=E2=80=93=
=E2=80=93and still do=E2=80=93=E2=80=93but it=E2=80=99s hard to monetize th=
at in a way that investors need her to. Even the most successful content si=
tes will never generate the same revenue as a successful product line, whic=
h is why content ventures often veer into product. That said, Paltrow raise=
d more than $50 million in her Series D, in 2020. I presume those investors=
 came in at that level because they saw an opportunity and wanted a return =
on their capital, via an exit, within a five-year term. That was almost fiv=
e years ago=E2=80=A6

