Exit Strategies

Lauren: Commerce needs content and content can have commerce, but in our tr=
ansactional world, where everything can be tracked, there=E2=80=99s an expe=
ctation and interest in making content a direct conversion tool. The realit=
y is that you can=E2=80=99t rely on that. Do you think there=E2=80=99s some=
thing that Goop could have done better with the power they had on the conte=
nt side? Because it sounds like most people who worked on editorial, if not=
 all of them, no longer work there.

Rachel: To get that big exit, Goop had to go into product, and that=E2=80=
=99s a tricky thing, because Paltrow built her brand by recommending and ta=
lking honestly about the things she loves, uses, and actually buys. You ins=
tantly lose credibility when you start your own product lines because, ulti=
mately, your goal is to sell your own stuff more than other people=E2=80=99=
s stuff.
At that point, you effectively can no longer do the thing that attracted pe=
ople to your brand in the first place.

Look, it=E2=80=99s hard to establish yourself as a content business and the=
n turn into a product brand; it=E2=80=99s easier to start with product and =
then also produce good content. I do think it=E2=80=99s possible to scale f=
rom content to commerce=E2=80=94Emily Weiss did it with Glossier=E2=80=94bu=
t it requires a discipline that Goop never had. If Paltrow only focused on =
one thing, or fewer things, and went deep in one category, it may have work=
ed. Launching into every single category looks like a money grab=E2=80=A6 b=
ecause it is a money grab, right? It=E2=80=99s better to be really good at =
fewer things than to be not great at many things. That was Goop=E2=80=99s d=
ownfall.

Lauren: Why do you think beauty hasn=E2=80=99t clicked the way it should ha=
ve? When Gwyneth first did beauty, she had Juice Beauty as a partner, and t=
hen it became its own thing, and then Goop put its
lower-price line at Target, which you reported was a flop ( https://puck.ne=
ws/gwyneth-paltrow-beauty-makeover-for-goop/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%2811%2F6%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ).

Rachel: Goop=E2=80=99s beauty line should have worked. It=E2=80=99s a misse=
d opportunity of epic proportions that it hasn=E2=80=99t seen the success o=
f other skincare and makeup brands that came out around the same time with =
similar propositions. Besides having no discipline, Goop never had the righ=
t leaders or C.P.G. infrastructure to set it up for success. There was neve=
r a strong operator to lead the charge, to oversee and scale the wholesale =
business=E2=80=94because, as we know, strong retail relationships are criti=
cal to a beauty brand=E2=80=99s success.

Goop took off in popularity during an era when V.C.s valued beauty brands l=
ike tech companies and D.T.C.
was king, but all that has changed. Retail is a very specific skill set, an=
d they probably didn=E2=80=99t have a person who knew how to work with Seph=
ora, Ulta, etcetera. When Gwyneth came out with skincare in 2016, it seemed=
 like it wasn=E2=80=99t the priority=E2=80=93=E2=80=93there was this robust=
 content arm, and all of these other things that they were doing. To build =
a beauty brand at scale, it would have needed to be the main focus, and it =
just wasn=E2=80=99t.

Lauren: They don=E2=80=99t half-ass anything=E2=80=94which doesn=E2=80=99t =
mean they do it right. There=E2=80=99s a desire to do it well, but I think =
you pinpointed the thing: They=E2=80=99ve never had the right operators, an=
d ultimately, the onus is on Gwyneth. Venture investors don=E2=80=99t butt =
into businesses a lot; they=E2=80=99re not operators or private equity, who=
 will bring in an operator to babysit. Everything Goop=E2=80=99s done is wi=
th intention=E2=80=93=E2=80=93it=E2=80=99s just that the execution and stra=
tegy hasn=E2=80=99t been as high or clear, because they don=E2=80=99t have =
that
bench of executives.

It=E2=80=99s easy to scrutinize because Gwyneth is very public. It=E2=80=99=
s also easy to see all the mistakes, and the big mistake is exactly what yo=
u=E2=80=99re saying=E2=80=93=E2=80=93trying to do five million things at on=
ce and not having anywhere near the right people to do those five million t=
hings. So what do you think their exit possibilities are at this point?

Rachel: You=E2=80=99ve said before that Goop could sell to a licensing firm=
, or a group that owns middle-of-the-road beauty brands, and there=E2=80=99=
s a chance they could break the businesses up and sell them off that way. T=
he company has been clear that its focuses are food, fashion, and beauty. I=
 think food and beauty are the two biggest opportunities. A person close to=
 Goop told me the company actually increased its revenue projections for 20=
24, which I=E2=80=99m sure is largely due to Goop Kitchen, the food deliver=
y concept that=E2=80=99s already reached =E2=80=9Ccompany-level profitabili=
ty.=E2=80=9D Excluding the Target
line, beauty=E2=80=99s had some momentum and a bunch of new launches lately=
=2E If Goop can get out of its own way=20=
and hire seasoned beauty executives wi=
th deep retail expertise, beauty could still become what it always should h=
ave been for them.

That=E2=80=99s it from Rachel and me. P.S.: congrats to our partners who cr=
eate The Best & Brightest ( https://puck.news/category/washington/?utm_camp=
aign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F6%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io =
), Puck=E2=80=99s excellent daily political product, for their unmatched re=
porting this election cycle.

Until tomorrow,
Lauren

