          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Just about every ce=
lebrity brand that=E2=80=99s glimmered into existence in the last decade ha=
s tried to model itself after Goop, the <b>Gwyneth</b> <b>Paltrow</b> lifes=
tyle venture that launched as a newsletter, in 2008, but has since expanded=
 into beauty, apparel, fine jewelry, cookware, and sex toys, not to mention=
 wellness summits, television, and a food delivery service, among other thi=
ngs. Lately, the company has entered a weird adolescent phase=E2=80=94no lo=
nger a startup, but not yet a profitable <i>business</i>, wielding outsize =
influence relative to its financial health. <br/><br/>The company has raise=
d more than $140 million to date, according to PitchBook, including a Serie=
s D in 2020 that valued the company at $380 million, <i>pre-money</i>. Four=
 years later, Goop is still not profitable and in the throes of yet another=
 restructuring that has
resulted in <i>three</i> rounds of layoffs since the summer=E2=80=94most re=
cently last week=E2=80=94which looks like an effort to slim down to satisfy=
 the board and position itself for potential suitors.<br/> <br/>And yet, wh=
ile the company has struggled to grow beyond its founder=E2=80=99s polarizi=
ng (but not <i>too</i> polarizing) persona, Goop endures because it is, per=
haps, the only <i>true</i> celebrity lifestyle brand. Paltrow has managed t=
o annoy and entice in equal measure, serving up self-deprecating grandiosit=
y, combined with impeccable taste and an <i>almost</i>-attainable life that=
 you, too, can sample by buying the serum she uses or taking $75 <b>Tracy A=
nderson</b> group classes in the Hamptons. Below, Lauren and I discuss why =
people care about Goop so much, how the company lost its way, and what a po=
tential exit could look like.<br/></td>
         </tr>
