          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>Rachel: </b>Gwyn=
eth is a celebrity and a founder, which are two different things, but she=
=E2=80=99s combined them in a way that magnifies each of those roles. Goop =
remains an anomaly when it comes to celebrity-founded brands because, typic=
ally, celebrities are founders in name only. Famous people usually lend the=
ir likeness, and involvement in their brands is more similar to a licensing=
 agreement. Gwyneth=E2=80=99s obviously way more than that=E2=80=93=E2=80=
=93she truly built a business influenced by her absurd life. Everyone wants=
 to do that, but no one else has in this way. She=E2=80=99s this Academy Aw=
ard-winning actress, a media staple for decades, a style icon, etcetera=E2=
=80=93=E2=80=93and then she actually started a real business that=E2=80=99s=
 authentic to her, like a modern <b>Martha Stewart</b>. She=E2=80=99s an ou=
tlier, and that=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99re talking about her now, 16 years=
 in.<br/>
<br/><b>Lauren: </b>What place does Goop serve in the ecosystem of the star=
tup world? <br/> <br/><b>Rachel:</b> If we look at contemporary brands in b=
eauty or fashion that were founded between 2008 and 2012, they either becam=
e profitable or they disappeared. Goop is not profitable, but it=E2=80=99s =
still around and still extremely relevant, with outsize influence compared =
to the actual size of the business. A friend texted me the other day after =
reading Line Sheet and said, =E2=80=9CI had no idea, I thought Goop was doi=
ng really well,=E2=80=9D because Gwyneth is portrayed and covered in the me=
dia as this really successful C.E.O. with a strong business. That was her p=
erception, at least. If not for Gwyneth=E2=80=99s relevance in culture, I d=
on=E2=80=99t know if Goop would be around.<br/> <br/><b>Lauren: </b>When Go=
op started, it had <i>so much</i> traction because Paltrow is a great edito=
r. She has a point of view, and she=E2=80=99s not afraid to present it. The=
 content was exciting, fun, juicy, and
entertaining. Then they started layering in other advertising and commercia=
l opportunities, which makes sense. There=E2=80=99s a multibrand retail exp=
erience, a fast-casual food vertical, her clothing, beauty, and more. Indiv=
idually, these are all interesting businesses, but altogether, that sort of=
 diversification can create a cloudy revenue picture and make a company a l=
ot less attractive to sell. When you look at the trajectory=E2=80=94launchi=
ng in 2008, getting advertising pretty quickly thereafter, opening multibra=
nd retail in the early 2010s, then launching products afterward, and now le=
aning into food=E2=80=94when do you think the business became more complica=
ted to sell? <br/> <br/><b>Rachel: </b>What was originally captivating, and=
 what remains captivating, is Gwyneth=E2=80=99s point of view. People wante=
d to read that initial newsletter because she has good taste. We wanted to =
know what she was eating, what exercise she was doing, where she was going,=
 tips for the best hotels, all of
those things. That=E2=80=99s what people wanted to know from <i>her</i>=E2=
=80=93=E2=80=93and still do=E2=80=93=E2=80=93but it=E2=80=99s hard to monet=
ize that in a way that investors need her to. Even the most successful cont=
ent sites will never generate the same revenue as a successful product line=
, which is why content ventures often veer into product. That said, Paltrow=
 raised more than $50 million in her Series D, in 2020. I presume those inv=
estors came in at that level because they saw an opportunity and wanted a r=
eturn on their capital, via an exit, within a five-year term. That was almo=
st five years ago=E2=80=A6<br/></td>
