          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>Lauren: </b>Comm=
erce needs content and content can have commerce, but in our transactional =
world, where everything can be tracked, there=E2=80=99s an expectation and =
interest in making content a direct conversion tool. The reality is that yo=
u can=E2=80=99t rely on that. Do you think there=E2=80=99s something that G=
oop could have done better with the power they had on the content side? Bec=
ause it sounds like most people who worked on editorial, if not all of them=
, no longer work there.<br/> <br/><b>Rachel: </b>To get that big exit, Goop=
 had to go into product, and that=E2=80=99s a tricky thing, because Paltrow=
 built her brand by recommending and talking honestly about the things she =
loves, uses, and actually buys. You instantly lose credibility when you sta=
rt your own product lines because, ultimately, your goal is to sell your ow=
n stuff more than other people=E2=80=99s stuff.
At that point, you effectively can no longer do the thing that attracted pe=
ople to your brand in the first place. <br/><br/>Look, it=E2=80=99s hard to=
 establish yourself as a content business and then turn into a product bran=
d; it=E2=80=99s easier to start with product and then also produce good con=
tent. I do think it=E2=80=99s possible to scale from content to commerce=E2=
=80=94<b>Emily Weiss</b> did it with Glossier=E2=80=94but it requires a dis=
cipline that Goop never had. If Paltrow only focused on one thing, or fewer=
 things, and went deep in one category, it may have worked. Launching into =
every single category looks like a money grab=E2=80=A6 because it <i>is</i>=
 a money grab, right? It=E2=80=99s better to be really good at fewer things=
 than to be not great at many things. That was Goop=E2=80=99s downfall.<br/=
> <br/><b>Lauren:</b> Why do you think beauty hasn=E2=80=99t clicked the wa=
y it should have? When Gwyneth first did beauty, she had Juice Beauty as a =
partner, and then it became its own thing, and then Goop put its
lower-price line at Target, which you reported was a <u><a href=3D"https://=
email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUQTlCUGlJUld=
ZZTdqcklEQ2c2QT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvZ3d5bmV0aC1wYWx0cm93LW=
JlYXV0eS1tYWtlb3Zlci1mb3ItZ29vcC8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUxpbmUrU2hlZXQrLStTVUJTQ=
1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMSUyRjYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW8iLCJp=
bnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjE5NDk2MTh9/2ffcc80a3e=
e894e9286acb919da0218e866b76d5ece89325d289797ce9a3c29f" style=3D"color:#d40=
000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">flop</a></u>.<br/>=
 <br/><b>Rachel:</b> Goop=E2=80=99s beauty line should have worked. It=E2=
=80=99s a missed opportunity of epic proportions that it hasn=E2=80=99t see=
n the success of other skincare and makeup brands that came out around the =
same time with similar propositions. Besides having no discipline, Goop nev=
er had the right leaders or C.P.G. infrastructure to set it up for success.=
 There was never a strong operator to lead the charge, to oversee and scale=
 the wholesale business=E2=80=94because, as we know, strong retail relation=
ships are <i>critical</i> to a beauty brand=E2=80=99s success. <br/><br/>Go=
